50|$|At age 54, Charles Henderson {{was elected}} Governor of Alabama. He was sworn into office on January 18, 1915. During his term, the state {{legislature}} passed a <b>tax</b> <b>revision</b> law, a primary election law, and a prohibition law. Henderson was personally opposed to prohibition, and vetoed a law against alcohol advertising. Legislature ignored his veto and passed the law anyway; in 1915, legislature went {{a step further and}} banned the sale of whiskey in Alabama. Henderson again vetoed this law and was overruled. Despite his personal disagreement with them, Henderson upheld and enforced both of these laws.|$|E
