40|$|GOVERNMENT PENSION PLANS. INITIATIVE CONSTITUTIONAL AMENDMENT. After January 1, 1985, {{requires}} {{enrollment in}} Federal Social Security of every newly hired or elected person of every city, county, tax funded or publicly owned operation, and the state; prohibits adding anyone to preexisting pension plans of these governmental entities; and restricts use of tax and general assessments funds for these newly hired or elected persons {{to use for}} Federal Social Security. Prohibits increase in property taxes inconsistent with Article XIIIA if additional or excess funds are required for pensions. Requires real estate <b>tax</b> rate <b>revision</b> downward when savings occurs. Makes other provisions. Summary of estimate by Legislative Analyst and Director of Finance of fiscal impact on state and local governments: There would be substantial savings {{to the state and}} local governments, probably about $ 230 million in 1985, the first full year of operation. These annual savings would increase substantially over time...|$|R
40|$|Sorry, {{the full}} text of this article is not {{available}} in Huskie Commons. Please click on the alternative location to access it. 221 p. The purpose of the dissertation is to determine the effect of variables hypothesized to be most important in changing the strength of tax expenditure claims on state financial resources and to determine if some types of tax expenditure claims might respond differently to those variables. Tax expenditures are conceptualized as features of tax policy that eliminate or reduce the tax liability of certain groups or categories of taxpayers. They represent claims on financial resources, just like budget requests that receive direct appropriations. They are "weak" or "strong" {{to the extent that they}} are successful in becoming and/or remaining part of the tax code. A market-based theory of budgeting was employed to deduce causal variables and hypotheses. Four causal variables [...] fiscal condition, the tax burden, legislative budget procedures that expose tax expenditures to scrutiny and competition, and the availability of information about tax expenditures [...] when found in certain ideal combinations, were hypothesized to either minimize or maximize the strength of tax expenditure claims. A comparative case study methodology was used to evaluate the effect of the causal variables on tax expenditure claims. Four states were selected for study: Michigan, Minnesota, Pennsylvania, and Wisconsin. Changes in tax expenditure provisions were examined in the four states over a fourteen-year period, 1980 - 1993. The case studies also examined income <b>tax</b> <b>revisions</b> where <b>tax</b> expenditures were repealed in order to reduce marginal rates. The four causal variables were found to be influential in determining the strength of tax expenditure claims. However, tax expenditure claims can also be weakened when states attempt to reduce the burden in one tax by repealing tax expenditures that apply to another tax, thus shifting the tax burden from one tax to another. Tax expenditures that are targeted at increasing investment to spur economic development can be very strong claims, even when the combination of causal variables predicts weak tax expenditure claims. Efforts to reduce high marginal income tax rates were also found to weaken tax expenditure claims...|$|R
40|$|The 2001 <b>tax</b> <b>revision</b> began a phaseout of {{the estate}} tax, by {{increasing}} exemptions and lowering rates. The estate tax {{is scheduled to be}} repealed in 2010 and a provision to tax appreciation on inherited assets (in excess of a limit) will be substituted. The 2001 tax provisions sunset, however, so that absent a change making them permanent the estate tax will revert, in 2011, to prior, pre- 2001, law...|$|E
